<p>The Trip to Bountiful is a 1985 American <ref target="/wiki/Drama_(film_and_television)" title="Drama (film and television)">drama film</ref> directed by <ref target="/wiki/Peter_Masterson" title="Peter Masterson">Peter Masterson</ref> and starring <ref target="/wiki/Geraldine_Page" title="Geraldine Page">Geraldine Page</ref>, <ref target="/wiki/John_Heard_(actor)" title="John Heard (actor)">John Heard</ref>, <ref target="/wiki/Carlin_Glynn" title="Carlin Glynn">Carlin Glynn</ref>, <ref target="/wiki/Richard_Bradford_(actor)" title="Richard Bradford (actor)">Richard Bradford</ref> and <ref target="/wiki/Rebecca_De_Mornay" title="Rebecca De Mornay">Rebecca De Mornay</ref>. It was adapted by <ref target="/wiki/Horton_Foote" title="Horton Foote">Horton Foote</ref> from his <ref target="/wiki/The_Trip_to_Bountiful_(play)" title="The Trip to Bountiful (play)"> play of the same name</ref>. The film features a soundtrack by J.A.C. Redford featuring <ref class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Will_Thompson" title="Will Thompson">Will Thompson</ref>'s "<ref target="/wiki/Softly_and_Tenderly" title="Softly and Tenderly">Softly and Tenderly</ref>" sung by <ref target="/wiki/Cynthia_Clawson" title="Cynthia Clawson">Cynthia Clawson</ref>.<ref target="#cite_note-tims-2">[2]</ref> Geraldine Page won the <ref target="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Actress" title="Academy Award for Best Actress">Academy Award for Best Actress</ref> for her performance as Mrs. Watts and Horton Foote was nominated for the <ref target="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Adapted_Screenplay" title="Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay">Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay</ref>.</p>
<p>The film is partially set in the titular community of Bountiful, a fictitious Texas town. Although part of the film is set in <ref target="/wiki/Houston" title="Houston">Houston</ref>, <ref target="/wiki/Texas" title="Texas">Texas</ref> (as was the original play), the movie was shot in <ref target="/wiki/Dallas" title="Dallas">Dallas</ref>.</p>

